snippet.textDisplay: Hi I’m Korean and i just wanted to say JjamPpong and Neoguri is just not the same thing. Neoguri is basically a spicy ramen with some seafood taste in it. And although Neoguri is referred as “udon ramen” in Korea, it’s actually just ramen noodles, exactly the same noodles with Jjapaghetti. Really appreciate the effort but there was no need in creating two different type of noodles. Also to add on, both Jjajangmyeon and Jjamppong are based on Chinese cuisine and they go under the category of Korean Chinese cuisine. We would never combine the two dishes, and it’s often the biggest dilema of Koreans which dish to choose to order!
snippet.textOriginal: Hi I’m Korean and i just wanted to say JjamPpong and Neoguri is just not the same thing. Neoguri is basically a spicy ramen with some seafood taste in it. snippet.textDisplay:
I believe the Jiapaguri [Ram-don] is one of the creatively created variety of instant noodles we have here in Asia; in what the West would call "Ramen" at one glance. But being that it's part of the instant noodle that's totally inexpensive, I'm glad that we Asians (from China, Japan, Korea to Southeast Asia like Malaysia, Singapore and Indonesia) are exposed to these types of instant noodles.

Although the Ram-don featured in the movie specifically used 'Chapahetti' and 'Neoguri', they're still part of the instant noodles that we Asians can easily find them at our convenient stores.

snippet.textDisplay: I'm absolutely nitpicking here but I'd like to point out that Korea and Japan is in the middle of the most bitter trade war since the WWII. I don't know how close Japanese beef is to Korean beef taste-wise but if your goal was to recreate the dish Korean style, I can tell you with confidence that no Korean would ever use Japanese beef in substitute for Korean beef. Good old American beef would have been fine. Besides, ever since Fukushima nuclear disaster, which is still leaking nuclear waste even today, a lot of Japanese food stuffs have been banned by many nation due to the worries of the radioactive contamination. That is something to keep in mind when you shop for food next time. Lovely video, btw. Throughly enjoyed watching it!
